**Definition**
Pages in jQuery Mobile are individual screen containers inside a single HTML file, each represented using a `<div>` with `data-role="page"`.

**Types**

* Single-page structure
* Multi-page structure (multiple pages in one HTML file)

**Working**
Each page is identified by an `id`. jQuery Mobile loads and displays them using Ajax navigation, applying transitions and maintaining browser history.

**Diagrams (text)**

```
<div data-role="page" id="home"> … </div>
<div data-role="page" id="about"> … </div>
```

**Advantages**

* Easy multi-screen navigation
* Reduced page load time
* Smooth transitions and history support

**Disadvantages**

* Large HTML files if many pages
* Harder to manage in big apps

**Examples**

```html
<div data-role="page" id="home">
  <div data-role="header"><h1>Home</h1></div>
  <div data-role="content"><p>Welcome!</p></div>
</div>
```

**Short code snippets**

```html
<a href="#home" data-transition="slide">Go to Home</a>
```

**Applications**

* Multi-page mobile websites
* Navigation-based interfaces
* Simple mobile apps using HTML/CSS/JS
